<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-properties-of-riemann-integrals"
  xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Properties of Riemann Integrals</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      The Darboux definition gives a practical criterion for integrability:
      a bounded function is integrable exactly when some partition makes the
      upper and lower sums arbitrarily close. We now use this criterion to
      prove the basic algebraic and order properties of the integral, and then
      to identify some important classes of integrable functions.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-basic-properties-of-the-integral">
    <title>Basic Properties</title>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-basic-properties-riemann-integral">
      <title>Basic Properties of the Integral</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>f,g \in R[a,b]</m>, and let <m>c \in \R</m>.
        </p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              The functions <m>f+g</m> and <m>cf</m> belong to
              <m>R[a,b]</m>, and
              <me>
                \int_a^b (f+g)=\int_a^b f+\int_a^b g,
                \qquad
                \int_a^b (cf)=c\int_a^b f.
              </me>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              If <m>f(x) \le g(x)</m> for every <m>x \in [a,b]</m>, then
              <me>
                \int_a^b f \le \int_a^b g.
              </me>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              If <m>a \lt c \lt b</m>, then the restrictions of <m>f</m> to
              <m>[a,c]</m> and <m>[c,b]</m> are integrable, and
              <me>
                \int_a^b f=\int_a^c f+\int_c^b f.
              </me>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              If <m>|f(x)| \le M</m> for every <m>x \in [a,b]</m>, then
              <me>
                \left|\int_a^b f\right| \le M|b-a|.
              </me>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          We begin with part (1). Let <m>I_f=\int_a^b f</m> and
          <m>I_g=\int_a^b g</m>, and fix <m>\varepsilon \gt 0</m>. By the
          <xref ref="prop-integrability-criterion-darboux" text="title"/>,
          there are partitions <m>P_f</m> and <m>P_g</m> of <m>[a,b]</m> such
          that
          <me>
            U(P_f,f)-L(P_f,f) \lt \frac{\varepsilon}{2},
            \qquad
            U(P_g,g)-L(P_g,g) \lt \frac{\varepsilon}{2}.
          </me>
          Let <m>P=P_f \cup P_g</m>. Since refinement decreases upper sums and
          increases lower sums,
          <me>
            U(P,f)-L(P,f) \lt \frac{\varepsilon}{2},
            \qquad
            U(P,g)-L(P,g) \lt \frac{\varepsilon}{2}.
          </me>
        </p>

        <p>
          For each subinterval <m>I_i</m> of <m>P</m>, let
          <m>m_i^f,M_i^f</m> and <m>m_i^g,M_i^g</m> be the infima and suprema
          of <m>f</m> and <m>g</m> on <m>I_i</m>. Then
          <me>
            m_i^f+m_i^g \le \inf_{x \in I_i}(f(x)+g(x)),
            \qquad
            \sup_{x \in I_i}(f(x)+g(x)) \le M_i^f+M_i^g.
          </me>
          Summing over the partition gives
          <me>
            L(P,f)+L(P,g) \le L(P,f+g) \le U(P,f+g) \le U(P,f)+U(P,g).
          </me>
          Hence
          <me>
            U(P,f+g)-L(P,f+g)
            \le
            \bigl(U(P,f)-L(P,f)\bigr)+\bigl(U(P,g)-L(P,g)\bigr)
            \lt \varepsilon.
          </me>
          So <m>f+g</m> is integrable.
        </p>

        <p>
          Also, because <m>I_f</m> lies between <m>L(P,f)</m> and
          <m>U(P,f)</m>, and similarly for <m>I_g</m>, we have
          <me>
            I_f+I_g-\varepsilon
            \lt
            L(P,f)+L(P,g)
            \le
            \int_a^b (f+g)
            \le
            U(P,f)+U(P,g)
            \lt
            I_f+I_g+\varepsilon.
          </me>
          Since <m>\varepsilon</m> is arbitrary,
          <m>\int_a^b (f+g)=I_f+I_g</m>.
        </p>

        <p>
          For scalar multiples, let <m>P=\{x_0,\dots,x_n\}</m> be any
          partition, and let <m>m_i,M_i</m> be the infima and suprema of
          <m>f</m> on <m>[x_{i-1},x_i]</m>. If <m>c \ge 0</m>, then the infimum
          and supremum of <m>cf</m> on the same interval are <m>cm_i</m> and
          <m>cM_i</m>. If <m>c \lt 0</m>, they are <m>cM_i</m> and <m>cm_i</m>.
          In either case,
          <me>
            U(P,cf)-L(P,cf)=|c|\bigl(U(P,f)-L(P,f)\bigr).
          </me>
          Hence <m>cf</m> is integrable. When <m>c \ge 0</m>,
          <me>
            L(P,cf)=cL(P,f),
            \qquad
            U(P,cf)=cU(P,f),
          </me>
          and the same squeeze argument as above gives
          <m>\int_a^b (cf)=c\int_a^b f</m>. When <m>c \lt 0</m>, the same
          conclusion follows from the identities
          <me>
            L(P,cf)=cU(P,f),
            \qquad
            U(P,cf)=cL(P,f).
          </me>
        </p>

        <p>
          For part (2), if <m>f(x) \le g(x)</m> on <m>[a,b]</m>, then on every
          subinterval of every partition <m>P</m> the infimum and supremum of
          <m>f</m> are at most the corresponding infimum and supremum of
          <m>g</m>. Thus
          <me>
            L(P,f) \le L(P,g)
            \qquad\text{and}\qquad
            U(P,f) \le U(P,g).
          </me>
          Since <m>\int_a^b f \le U(P,f)</m> and <m>L(P,g) \le \int_a^b g</m>
          for every partition <m>P</m>, it follows that
          <m>\int_a^b f \le \int_a^b g</m>.
        </p>

        <p>
          For part (3), let <m>I=\int_a^b f</m> and fix <m>\varepsilon \gt 0</m>.
          By the <xref ref="prop-integrability-criterion-darboux" text="title"/>,
          there is a partition <m>P</m> of <m>[a,b]</m> such that
          <m>U(P,f)-L(P,f) \lt \varepsilon/2</m>. If <m>c \notin P</m>, adjoin
          <m>c</m> to obtain a refinement; the gap does not increase. Write
          <m>P_1</m> and <m>P_2</m> for the induced partitions of
          <m>[a,c]</m> and <m>[c,b]</m>. Then
          <me>
            L(P,f)=L(P_1,f)+L(P_2,f),
            \qquad
            U(P,f)=U(P_1,f)+U(P_2,f),
          </me>
          so
          <me>
            \bigl(U(P_1,f)-L(P_1,f)\bigr)+\bigl(U(P_2,f)-L(P_2,f)\bigr)
            =
            U(P,f)-L(P,f)
            \lt
            \frac{\varepsilon}{2}.
          </me>
          Since each summand is nonnegative, both are less than
          <m>\varepsilon/2</m>. Therefore the restrictions of <m>f</m> to
          <m>[a,c]</m> and <m>[c,b]</m> are integrable.
        </p>

        <p>
          Let <m>I_1=\int_a^c f</m> and <m>I_2=\int_c^b f</m>. Because
          <m>I_1</m> and <m>I_2</m> lie between the corresponding lower and
          upper sums, we obtain
          <md>
            <mrow>
              I_1+I_2-\varepsilon
              \lt
              L(P_1,f)+L(P_2,f)
              =
              L(P,f)
              \le
              I,
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              I
              \le
              U(P,f)
              =
              U(P_1,f)+U(P_2,f)
              \lt
              I_1+I_2+\varepsilon.
            </mrow>
          </md>
          Hence <m>I=I_1+I_2</m>.
        </p>

        <p>
          Finally, for part (4), the hypothesis gives
          <m>-M \le f(x) \le M</m> on <m>[a,b]</m>. By part (2),
          <me>
            \int_a^b (-M) \le \int_a^b f \le \int_a^b M.
          </me>
          Since constant functions are integrable and
          <me>
            \int_a^b (-M)=-M(b-a),
            \qquad
            \int_a^b M=M(b-a),
          </me>
          we conclude that
          <me>
            -M(b-a) \le \int_a^b f \le M(b-a).
          </me>
          Therefore <m>\left|\int_a^b f\right| \le M(b-a)=M|b-a|</m>.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </theorem>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-step-functions">
    <title>Step Functions</title>

    <p>
      A function <m>s \colon [a,b] \to \R</m> is a
      <term>step function</term><idx>step function</idx> if there is a
      partition <m>P=\{x_0,\dots,x_n\}</m> of <m>[a,b]</m> and real numbers
      <m>c_1,\dots,c_n</m> such that
      <me>
        s=\sum_{i=1}^n c_i 1_{I_i},
      </me>
      where
      <me>
        I_i=[x_{i-1},x_i)
        \qquad (1 \le i \lt n),
        \qquad
        I_n=[x_{n-1},x_n].
      </me>
    </p>

    <p>
      If <m>J</m> is any subinterval of <m>[a,b]</m> with endpoints
      <m>c \le d</m>, then the indicator function <m>1_J</m> is Riemann
      integrable and
      <me>
        \int_a^b 1_J=d-c.
      </me>

      Indeed, let <m>\varepsilon \gt 0</m>. One may choose a partition that
      isolates the endpoints of <m>J</m> inside two subintervals of lengths
      less than <m>\varepsilon/2</m> each. Outside those short endpoint
      intervals the function is constant, so the upper and lower sums differ
      by at most <m>\varepsilon</m>. Thus <m>1_J</m> is integrable, and its
      integral is the length of <m>J</m>.
    </p>

    <proposition xml:id="prop-step-functions-integrable">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Every step function on <m>[a,b]</m> is Riemann integrable. More
          precisely, if
          <me>
            s=\sum_{i=1}^n c_i 1_{I_i}
          </me>
          for a partition <m>P=\{x_0,\dots,x_n\}</m> and the associated
          subintervals <m>I_i</m>, then
          <me>
            \int_a^b s=\sum_{i=1}^n c_i(x_i-x_{i-1}).
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          Each indicator function <m>1_{I_i}</m> is integrable, with
          <m>\int_a^b 1_{I_i}=x_i-x_{i-1}</m>. Therefore part (1) of
          <xref ref="thm-basic-properties-riemann-integral" text="title"/>
          shows that any linear combination
          <m>\sum_{i=1}^n c_i1_{I_i}</m> is integrable and that
          <me>
            \int_a^b s
            =
            \sum_{i=1}^n c_i \int_a^b 1_{I_i}
            =
            \sum_{i=1}^n c_i(x_i-x_{i-1}).
          </me>
        </p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-continuous-functions-of-integrable-functions">
    <title>Continuous Functions of Integrable Functions</title>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-continuous-composition-preserves-integrability">
      <title>Continuous Compositions Preserve Integrability</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Suppose <m>f \in R[a,b]</m>, let <m>m,M \in \R</m> satisfy
          <m>f([a,b]) \subseteq [m,M]</m>, and let
          <m>\phi \colon [m,M] \to \R</m> be continuous. Then
          <m>\phi \circ f \in R[a,b]</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>

    <p>
      A proof of this can be found in <xref ref="biblio-rudin-pma"/>. The
      same result holds for the more general Riemann-Stieltjes integral.
    </p>

    <p>
      The order of composition matters. There exist a Riemann integrable
      function <m>f</m> and a continuous function <m>\phi</m> such that
      <m>f \circ \phi</m> is not Riemann integrable; see
      <xref ref="biblio-lu-composition-integrable"/>.
    </p>

    <proposition xml:id="prop-product-of-integrable-functions">
      <statement>
        <p>
          If <m>f,g \in R[a,b]</m>, then <m>fg \in R[a,b]</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          By the <xref ref="thm-basic-properties-riemann-integral" text="title"/>,
          the functions <m>f+g</m>, <m>f</m>, and <m>g</m> are integrable. The
          function <m>t \mapsto t^2</m> is continuous on every closed bounded
          interval, so <xref
          ref="thm-continuous-composition-preserves-integrability"
          text="title"/> shows that <m>(f+g)^2</m>, <m>f^2</m>, and
          <m>g^2</m> are integrable. Since
          <me>
            fg=\frac12\bigl((f+g)^2-f^2-g^2\bigr),
          </me>
          another application of
          <xref ref="thm-basic-properties-riemann-integral" text="title"/>
          gives <m>fg \in R[a,b]</m>.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>

    <proposition xml:id="prop-absolute-value-integrable">
      <statement>
        <p>
          If <m>f \in R[a,b]</m>, then <m>|f| \in R[a,b]</m>. Moreover,
          <me>
            \left|\int_a^b f\right| \le \int_a^b |f|.
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          The function <m>t \mapsto |t|</m> is continuous, so
          <xref ref="thm-continuous-composition-preserves-integrability"
          text="title"/> shows that <m>|f|</m> is integrable.
        </p>

        <p>
          Since <m>-|f(x)| \le f(x) \le |f(x)|</m> on <m>[a,b]</m>, part (2)
          of <xref ref="thm-basic-properties-riemann-integral" text="title"/>
          gives
          <me>
            \int_a^b (-|f|) \le \int_a^b f \le \int_a^b |f|.
          </me>
          Part (1) of the same theorem implies
          <m>\int_a^b (-|f|)=-\int_a^b |f|</m>. Therefore
          <me>
            -\int_a^b |f|
            \le
            \int_a^b f
            \le
            \int_a^b |f|,
          </me>
          and hence <m>\left|\int_a^b f\right| \le \int_a^b |f|</m>.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>

  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-large-classes-of-integrable-functions">
    <title>Large Classes of Integrable Functions</title>

    <p>
      For <m>n \ge 1</m>, the <term>uniform <m>n</m>-partition</term><idx><h>uniform partition</h></idx>
      of <m>[a,b]</m> is the partition
      <me>
        P_n([a,b])=\left\{a=x_0 \lt x_1 \lt \cdots \lt x_n=b\right\},
      </me>
      where
      <me>
        \Delta x_i = x_i-x_{i-1}=\frac{b-a}{n}
        \qquad (1 \le i \le n).
      </me>
      When the interval is clear from the context, we simply write
      <m>P_n</m>.
    </p>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-continuous-function-integrable">
      <title>Continuous Functions Are Integrable</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Every continuous function on a closed bounded interval is Riemann
          integrable.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          Let <m>f \colon [a,b] \to \R</m> be continuous, and let
          <m>\varepsilon \gt 0</m>. By
          <xref ref="thm-continuous-on-closed-bounded-interval-uniformly-continuous"/>,
          <m>f</m> is uniformly continuous on <m>[a,b]</m>. Therefore there
          exists <m>\delta \gt 0</m> such that
          <me>
            |f(x)-f(x')| \lt \frac{\varepsilon}{b-a}
          </me>
          whenever <m>x,x' \in [a,b]</m> and <m>|x-x'| \lt \delta</m>.
        </p>

        <p>
          Choose <m>n</m> so large that <m>(b-a)/n \lt \delta</m>, and let
          <m>P_n=\{x_0,\dots,x_n\}</m> be the uniform <m>n</m>-partition of
          <m>[a,b]</m>. For each subinterval <m>I_i=[x_{i-1},x_i]</m>, the
          restriction of <m>f</m> to <m>I_i</m> is continuous, so the
          <xref ref="thm-extreme-value-theorem" text="title"/> gives points
          <m>x_i^*,x_i^{**} \in I_i</m> such that
          <me>
            M_i=f(x_i^*),
            \qquad
            m_i=f(x_i^{**}),
          </me>
          where <m>M_i</m> and <m>m_i</m> are the supremum and infimum of
          <m>f</m> on <m>I_i</m>.
        </p>

        <p>
          Since <m>|x_i^*-x_i^{**}| \le (b-a)/n \lt \delta</m>, we have
          <me>
            M_i-m_i
            =
            |f(x_i^*)-f(x_i^{**})|
            \lt
            \frac{\varepsilon}{b-a}.
          </me>
          Therefore
          <me>
            U(P_n,f)-L(P_n,f)
            =
            \sum_{i=1}^n (M_i-m_i)\Delta x_i
            \lt
            \frac{\varepsilon}{b-a}\sum_{i=1}^n \Delta x_i
            =
            \varepsilon.
          </me>
          By the <xref ref="prop-integrability-criterion-darboux" text="title"/>,
          <m>f</m> is integrable.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </theorem>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-monotone-function-integrable">
      <title>Monotone Functions Are Integrable</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Every monotone function on a closed bounded interval is Riemann
          integrable.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          First suppose that <m>f</m> is increasing on <m>[a,b]</m>. Let
          <m>P_n=\{x_0,\dots,x_n\}</m> be the uniform <m>n</m>-partition of
          <m>[a,b]</m>. Then on each subinterval <m>[x_{i-1},x_i]</m>,
          <me>
            M_i=f(x_i),
            \qquad
            m_i=f(x_{i-1}).
          </me>
          Hence
          <me>
            U(P_n,f)-L(P_n,f)
            =
            \sum_{i=1}^n (f(x_i)-f(x_{i-1}))\frac{b-a}{n}
            =
            \frac{b-a}{n}\bigl(f(b)-f(a)\bigr).
          </me>
          The right-hand side tends to <m>0</m> as <m>n \to \infty</m>, so the
          <xref ref="prop-integrability-criterion-darboux" text="title"/>
          shows that <m>f</m> is integrable.
        </p>

        <p>
          If <m>f</m> is decreasing, then <m>-f</m> is increasing, so the
          argument above shows that <m>-f</m> is integrable. By part (1) of
          <xref ref="thm-basic-properties-riemann-integral" text="title"/>,
          <m>f=-(-f)</m> is integrable as well.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </theorem>

    <example xml:id="eg-thomae-function">
      <statement>
        <p>
          The <term>Thomae function</term><idx>Thomae function</idx>
          <m>h \colon [0,1] \to \R</m> is defined by
          <me>
            h(x)=
            \begin{cases}
              \dfrac{1}{n} &amp; \text{if } x=\dfrac{m}{n} \text{ in lowest terms},\\
              0 &amp; \text{if } x \in [0,1]\setminus \Q.
            \end{cases}
          </me>
          This function is integrable on <m>[0,1]</m>, with
          <m>\int_0^1 h=0</m>, but it is neither continuous nor monotone on
          any nondegenerate subinterval of <m>[0,1]</m>.
        </p>

        <figure xml:id="fig-thomae-function">
          <caption>A plot of the Thomae function on <m>[0,1]</m>, showing
          sample values at rational points with denominator at most
          <m>10</m>.</caption>
          <image width="65%">
            <shortdescription>A point plot of the Thomae function on the interval from zero to one, with higher points at rationals having small denominators and lower points at rationals with larger denominators.</shortdescription>
            <latex-image>
\begin{tikzpicture}
\begin{axis}[
  width=10cm,
  height=5.8cm,
  axis lines=middle,
  xmin=-0.02, xmax=1.02,
  ymin=-0.02, ymax=1.05,
  xtick={0,0.25,0.5,0.75,1},
  ytick={0,0.2,0.4,0.6,0.8,1},
  xlabel={$x$},
  ylabel={$y$},
  clip=false
]
  \addplot[black, thick, domain=0:1, samples=2] {0};
  \addplot[only marks, blue!70!black, mark=*, mark size=1.2pt] coordinates {
    (0.000000,1.000000)
    (0.100000,0.100000)
    (0.111111,0.111111)
    (0.125000,0.125000)
    (0.142857,0.142857)
    (0.166667,0.166667)
    (0.200000,0.200000)
    (0.222222,0.111111)
    (0.250000,0.250000)
    (0.285714,0.142857)
    (0.300000,0.100000)
    (0.333333,0.333333)
    (0.375000,0.125000)
    (0.400000,0.200000)
    (0.428571,0.142857)
    (0.444444,0.111111)
    (0.500000,0.500000)
    (0.555556,0.111111)
    (0.571429,0.142857)
    (0.600000,0.200000)
    (0.625000,0.125000)
    (0.666667,0.333333)
    (0.700000,0.100000)
    (0.714286,0.142857)
    (0.750000,0.250000)
    (0.777778,0.111111)
    (0.800000,0.200000)
    (0.833333,0.166667)
    (0.857143,0.142857)
    (0.875000,0.125000)
    (0.888889,0.111111)
    (0.900000,0.100000)
    (1.000000,1.000000)
  };
\end{axis}
\end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
          </image>
        </figure>

        <p>
          By <xref ref="prop-q-dense-in-r"/> and the argument from
          <xref ref="eg-dirichlet-upper-lower-integrals"/>, every
          nondegenerate subinterval of <m>[0,1]</m> contains both rational and
          irrational numbers. Thus, if <m>\alpha \lt q \lt \beta</m> with
          <m>\alpha,\beta</m> irrational and <m>q</m> rational, then
          <me>
            h(\alpha)=0,
            \qquad
            h(q) \gt 0,
            \qquad
            h(\beta)=0,
          </me>
          so <m>h</m> cannot be increasing or decreasing on that interval.
          Also, if <m>q \in [0,1] \cap \Q</m>, choose irrational numbers
          <m>\alpha_n \to q</m>. Then <m>h(\alpha_n)=0 \to 0</m>, while
          <m>h(q) \gt 0</m>, so <m>h</m> is not continuous at <m>q</m>. Since
          rationals are dense, <m>h</m> is not continuous on any
          nondegenerate subinterval.
        </p>

        <p>
          Every nondegenerate subinterval of <m>[0,1]</m> contains irrational
          numbers, so the infimum of <m>h</m> on each such interval is
          <m>0</m>. Hence every lower sum of <m>h</m> is <m>0</m>.
        </p>

        <p>
          To control the upper sums, fix <m>N \in \N</m> and let
          <me>
            H_N=\{x \in [0,1] : h(x) \ge 1/N\}.
          </me>
          If <m>x \in H_N</m>, then <m>x=m/n</m> in lowest terms with
          <m>1 \le n \le N</m>. Therefore <m>H_N</m> is finite. Choose
          pairwise disjoint closed intervals <m>J_x \subseteq [0,1]</m>, one
          for each <m>x \in H_N</m>, such that <m>x \in J_x</m> and the sum of
          their lengths is less than <m>1/N</m>. Let <m>P</m> be a partition
          containing all endpoints of these intervals.
        </p>

        <p>
          Any subinterval of <m>P</m> that is disjoint from
          <m>\bigcup_{x \in H_N} J_x</m> contains no point of <m>H_N</m>, so
          the supremum of <m>h</m> there is less than <m>1/N</m>. On the other
          subintervals, the supremum is at most <m>1</m>. It follows that
          <me>
            U(P,h)
            \le
            \sum_{x \in H_N} |J_x| + \frac{1}{N}
            \left(1-\sum_{x \in H_N} |J_x|\right)
            \lt
            \frac{1}{N}+\frac{1}{N}
            =
            \frac{2}{N}.
          </me>
          Since <m>N</m> is arbitrary, the
          <xref ref="prop-integrability-criterion-darboux" text="title"/>
          shows that <m>h</m> is integrable. Because every lower sum is
          <m>0</m>, we have <m>\int_0^1 h=0</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
  </subsection>
</section>
